==English==

===Etymology===
Old French '''mareschal''', from '''mare''' (horse) + '''schal''' (servant); akin to Old High German '''marahscalc''', from '''marah''' (horse) + '''scalc''' (servant), and probably Korean '''mar''' ([[말]]: horse), '''galgda''' ([[갉다]]: to rake), '''galkwi''' ([[갈퀴]], rake), '''halkwida''' ([[할퀴다]]: to rake), German '''[[Harke]]''' ([[rake]], [[harrow]]).

===Noun===
'''marshal'''

# A high-ranking officer in the household of a medieval prince or lord, who was originally in charge of the cavalry and later the military forces in general. 
# A military officer of the highest rank.
# A person in charge of the ceremonial arrangement and management of a gathering.
# A [[sheriff]]'s assistant.
# <!--WTF?--> An alternative spelling of [[mareschal]].
# <!--WTF?--> The highest ranking piece in the board game [[Stratego]].

'''Translations'''

* French: [[:fr:maréchal|maréchal]]
* German: [[:ge:Marschall|Marschall]]

===Verb===
'''to marshal'''
# to arrange [[troops]] etc in [[line]] for [[inspection]] or a [[parade]]
#(''be extension'') to arrange [[fact]]s etc in some methodical order
# to [[ceremoniously]] [[guide]], [[conduct]] or [[usher]]